{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_sixteen_ver01/data/sn88084205/00100478973/1908052801/0274.xml":{"full_text":"ft\nf\n4\nI\nu I\nv l kGi w ir r711V r I\nV\nT\nPanama City Pilot\nu\nPublished every Thursday\nBy The\nPanama City Pub Co\nG M West President and Editor\nTermsOne Year 100 Six Months 50c\nHates for advertising on application\nEntered as secondclass matter May 30th\n1907 at the post otllcc at Panama City Florida\nunder the Act of Congress of March 3 1879\nu\nPANAMA CITY FLA MAY 28 1908\nA Yearling\nWith its last issue the PILOT com\npleted an existence of one full year\n1he management takes this occasion\nto heartily thank those who have\nmade possible its steady and rapid\nincrease in circulation which for a\nsmall marooned sheet has been almost\nunprecedented Scarcely a day has\npassed but accessions have been made\nto its readers and as yet no one has\nstopped his paper\nIn the Salutatory in Number 1\nit was stated that the aim of the\nPILOT is to further the interests of\nthis portion of West Florida bringing\nimmigrants homoseekers to Wash\nington county advancing the up\nbuilding of Panama City hastening\nthe opening of our magnificent Deep I\nWater Harbor to the commerce of\nthe world and voicing public senti\nment on all vital issues of the day\nTo what extent the paper has ful\nfilled its promises is left to its readers\nto judge\nWhat the coming year will bring to\nthem can be best judged by the past\nNothing stands still in this world\nTnere is either progression or retro\ngression The management of the\nPILOT does not intend that it shall go\nbackwards and it should show a\nbetterment\nIt will within a short time have an\nopportunity tw be in closer touch with\nthe outside world through the railway\nconnection soon to be completed and\nit hopes ere another year has passed\nto be able to announce the opening\nof this harbor to the commerce of the\nworld\nIf its prosperity and increase of\nsubscribers in the coming year be as\nnumerous and uniform as has been\nthe case tu the past its management\nwill feel that it has been fairly suc\ncessful if it fails to achieve this it\nfrankly admits now that there will be\nno one to blame but itself\nFederal Injunctions\nIt is stated that no bill to modify\nthe power of the federal courts in the\nexercise of injunctions will be passed\nat this session of congress In the\nfeverish condition attendant upon a\npresidential campaign it is well that\nsuch important matters as changing\nlong existing laws be postponed to a\nmore opportune season\nIt is admitted by all thoughtful peo\nple that not only has the writ of in\njunction been abused but from the\npower to issue it being in the hands\nof unscrupulous unjudicial judges\nit may be a powerful instrument of\nharm and wrong doing\nThe Appellate Division of the Su\npremo Court of New York in a recent\ndecision upon several injunctions is\nsued by one of the judges of the city\nof New York prohibiting the police\nfrom enforcing the laws against hold\ning concerts and theatricals on Sun i\nOJ\nI\nday declare unanimously that these i\ninjunctions were illegitimate and\nshould never have been issued Here\nwere cases wherein a judge a servile\ntrimmer disgraced the judges ermine\nby pandering to lawlessness\nTo the contrary the necessity of re\ntaining the present powers of the\ncourts in the issuing of this process\nis most strongly presented in the\nrecent troubles at Pensacola where\nthrough failure of the State county\nand city officials to enforce the laws\nmob rule reigned and neither prop\nerty or life was secure Immediately j\nupon the federal courts issuing its\nmandate the mob was checked even\nby its announcement and peace\nreigned It was plainly understood\nthat defiance of it was equivalent to j\nbutting ones head against a stone\nwall and possibly the nearness of i\nthe walls of Forts Barrancas and I\nPickcns gave additional force to the\nwrit I\n1If IL v\nI\nThe Currency Bill\nI\nDespite the very favorable action\nof the House on the Vreeland bill it\nwas turned down most unceremoni\nously by the Senate and the Aldrich I\nbill adopted in its place\nI\nI This action caused a conference on\nI these bills which ends with an an j I\nnouncement by Senator Aldrich that\nthere is no possibility of an agree I\nment at this session and asking that I\na committee of nine senators and\nnine representatives be appointed to I\nhold sessions during the recess and I\nsubmit the results of their investiga I\ntions at the next session of congress I\nThis action of congress upon a mat\nter that was thought to be of vital I\nimportance when the session began I\nillustrates a peculiar feature of the\ncongress and the American people I\nalso in affairs of this kind When\ncongress assembled the panic was on\nand everyone was suffering Help\nwas demanded through that body and\nit was supposed that immediate action\nwould be taken\nSix months have passed and with\nthem the panic and also the shout\ning in congress for relief It is the\nold story of the shingleless roof\nWhen it rained it could not be re\npaired and when it was clear there\nwas no necessity of it Knowledge\nconies but Wisdom lingers\nRailway Number\nWith the completion of the Atlanta\nSt Andrews Bay R R to its ter\nminus at Panama City and the start\ning of a regular passenger service\nover its line to this point the PILOT\nwill get out a Special Railway Number\nThis number will have some features\nof importance to all interested in the\nBay country and in the history of\nrailways in this section\nIt will contain a reproduction of the\nfirst advertisement and tariff of the\nSt Joseph and lola Railroad Com\npany which was published in the\nSt Joseph Times upon the opening\nof the companys line between St Jo\nseph and lola with other items\nof history relative to this road to\ngether with illustrations It will be\nremembered that this was probably\nthe first of Floridas railroads as well\nas one of the first in the United States\nThis number will also contain the\nhistory of the inception promotion\nand construction of the Atlanta St\nAndrews Bay IL R from Dothan to\nPanama City the first of many\nprojected railroads to reach this por\ntion of the Gulf of Mexico and to fur\nnish an outlet landward for the grow\ning commerce of the Gulf\nTelepathic Politics\nll is admitted by many scientists\nwho have made a study of the action\nof the mind that there undoubtedly\nexists a telepathic influence of mind\nover mind regardless of propinquity\nOr in other words we may be in\nfluenced in our actions and even in\nour physical condition by the\nthoughts of a person far distant from\nus or by a number of persons think\ning intently regarding a matter that\ndoes or is to affect us\nAdmitting this to be a cause of in\nfluence what may be the result of\nsuch a condition politically as exists\ntoday It is admitted that Taft will\nbe the Republican and Bryan the\nDemocratic nominee for president\nIt is also generally admitted that\nBryan cannot be elected\nApplying the telepathic theory to\nthese conditions what effect is it\nhaving upon the probable success or\ndefeat of the candidates Is Bryan\nto be defeated by this telepathic in\nfluence rather than by the party or\nthe platform It would look as if\nthis were to be the result of telepathy\nin politics\nWest Floridians will be pleased to\nlearn that the Senate has approved\nof the nomination of Judge Sheppard\nThis gentleman has made good thus\nfar in his brief service as Judge of the\nFederal District court and has evi\ndenced a judicial bent that prophe\ncies well for his future career upon\nthe bench\nEditor Mayes of the Pensacola\nJournal went in at the First Primary\nwith a majority that speaks in no un\ncertain terms of his popularity among\nthe people Though an outspoken\nBryan delegate that cut no figure in\nthe vote which was cast for Frank\nL Hayes the man and not the dele\ngate\nHouse of Governors J\nOne of the unfortunate features of\nthe recent governors conference at\nthe White House was the movement\nto make permanent the gathering of\nthe governors Possibly the sugges\ntion grew out of enthusiasm and may\nbe excused uIlon that ground but the I\nidea of forming a House of Gov\nernors in these United States is ob I\nnoxious in the extreme unAmerican I\nlike and contrary to all the teachings i\nof the Constitution j\nThe Vashington Post speaking upon\nthe subject very pertinently says j\nThere is no room in the republic\nfor a House of Governors in any form\nunder any auspices through any pre\ntense States rights as recognized j\nby the Constitution Yes The gov\nernment of the nation by State exe j\ncutives Nonever We sincerely i\nhope the executives will show their I\npatriotism by refusing to organize as\na separate or distinctive body\nI\nI\nThe Price of Cotton\nTo the southern farmer just now the\nchit nil problems is the price of I\ncott lie cannot understand why i\nthe large promises of both the Farm\ners Union and the Southern Cotton I\nAssociation have all failed to be kept j\nand despite the best efforts of these\nI\norganizations the price of his money\ncrop has dropped to a point so far I\nbelow the 15 cent standard fixed by\nthem But there are farmers and\nfarmers and one of them out in\nTexas in a letter to the Dallas News\nhandles the question in this plain\nblunt sensible way\nIf you want a good price for cot\nton let us plant half of our land in\nsomething else raise more hogs and\nfeed and a 6000000 bale crop and\nwe will get as much for 6000000 as\nfor 13000000 and have what the other\nhalf makes in feed and hogs ahead\nsend our children to school more and\nlive at home and have a better time\nWe must stand by our merchants and\nour homo banks and stick together\nI\nas farmers and not get our neighbors\nI\nto plant less cotton and slip around\nand plant all our land in cotton\nDont blame your merchant for he\nwould rather pail you 15 cents for\ncotton than to py you 5 cents I\ndont want my merchant to pay me\n15 cents for cotton when he can get\nbut 10 cents Let us be consistent\nand not want to take more than we\nI are willing to give Let us look well\nto ourselves and see if we are not I\ntrying to do the very thing we are\nblaming other men for 1oingPen\nsacola Journal\nLooking Up\nTwo more railroads to inaugurate\npassenger service in Birmingham be\nfore another month three big sky\nscrapers to be well under way before\nthe year is out a large number of\nresidences and business buildings\nunder construction and early con\ntemplation quite a number of now\nenterprises projected and a gradual\nrevisal of active trade conditions all\nalong the line These are some of\nthe things that make the outlook for I\na return of prosperity in this district 1\nI\nmore than ordinarily encouraging\nBirmingham News\nI Restoring Prosperity\nI if industrial depressions were tran\nI\nsient affairs coming and going in a\nfortnight or a month publicity of this I\nsort might accomplish something by\nestablishing conditions on a firm I\nbasis before its duplicity should be I\ndiscovered But dull times are not I\nto be so quickly overcome Nothing\nexcept orders backed by specifica\nI tions will work their correction\nUntrue or halftrue reports cannot\nI\ni create orders at best they can only\nI I build up an extremely unstable va\nriety of artificial prosperity which\nI\nbenefits no one and eventually proves\n1\nan actual hindrance in the restora\ni tion of healthy and vigorous business\nI\ni conditions Iron Trade Review\nj\n1 Congress will probably adjourn this\ni week\ni\nTram moll defeated Ellis in the race\nfor Attorney General\nBeard comes out in favor of Flet\nt\n1 cher in the 2nd Primary\nPar ties are talking of erecting a\nS35OOU hotel at Flomaton\nI\nGov Comers right hand man Sena\ntor Ltisfc was overwhelmingly defeat\ned in the recent primaries in Ala\nI\n1 ama\nAnanta and\nSt Andrews Bay\nRail Road\nOnly direct Rail Route from Central and South Alabama\nand Georgia to the GULF COAST 1\n1\nTIME TABLE No 4\nIn effect Monday March 2 liOS\n1\nI I I I I\ntNo 3 I No 1 I DIS I STATION I tNo 2 f\nS Oanl I S20an1 I 0 I LvIothan Ala Ar I 7 oopln 1\n8aO I S50 I 10 I Ilodgeville I i5 I\n920 I 915 I 2 U I Cllllhpl1tl Fla I 55a I\nn40 11000 12G I Welchton I f1i11 I\nJ55 I 1120 I H I Cottondalt Fla t 515 I\n1025 I 1000 13S I Alfonl I 430 i\n1040 I 1115 141 t Round hake 1 115 I\n1055anll 11135ai11 146 i Compa I 100 I\n1140p1111 12BOp1n I 53 I Fol1ntnin 1 i20 I\n1220pnl I 10pnl I U LIAr Y 0l111gRtown IiV t 2 aopm I\nJ I J Pantuna City J I\nDaily except Sunday Daily Sunday only\nConnect at Cottondale L C N Dothan A t1 L C of Ca\nW F MCCLKLLAN And P J DOMKR Supt\nEAST BAY MAIL PASSENGER AND FREIGHT LINE\nCABIN LAUNCHES\nLeda y Leonore and Laura\nol IbicAl J rcm1oDiI\nPassenger Freight and Towing business promptly and satisfactorily at\ntended to Manager can be reached day or night by telephone from\nG C D Cos office Panama City or at home at Old Town\nEast Bay Mail leaves St Andrews each week day at 530 a m Arrives\nat Wetappo at 12 noon Leaves Wetappo atl p m Arrives ai\nSt Andrews at 630 p nl Makes stops at Panama City\nMillvilleCromanton Parker Cook FarnHlale and Allanton\nWill also stop on arrangement made at other points\nF A VlrllJ FRILL MANAGKK\nW C Holley Co\nSuccessors to C E Brackin Co\nDEALERS IN ALL KINDS OF\nNotions Feed Stuffs Etc\nCall and see them as they deliver freight to all points on the\nbay in and up to Five Dollars or more except feed\nST ANDREW FLORIDA\n1 l jfPt 1\nE Wo Masker\nIiColored 0 TOG R 4 PHS\nColored Souvenir Postal Cards and Books\nSTUDIO ST ANDREW FLA\nv zr U\nS\nFuneral Director and Embalming\nEverything Necessary for the care and\nBurial of the dead\nCaskets Coffins Burial Robes Suits Etc\nA H BRAKE\nST ANDREW FLORIDA\nt a\n1\nLaunch J4NE JONES\nI\ni\nI I\nI\nVYF\nwt r9 tl S\nw A ft\no yrwr\nJ\n\nr j 4\nA COMFORTABLE RELIABLE BOAT\nPassengers or Towing\no\nApply R R SHEPPARD St Andrew Fla\nPost Office Draw